revision.text:
'''Ancient''' and '''modern''' are terms used in [[heraldry]] to differentiate two different coats of arms used at different periods by a family or other bearer. Reasons for changing arms have been numerous, the most famous being the change in the [[Royal arms of France|French royal arms]] to show three fleurs-de-lis instead of ''semee de lis'', possibly to symbolize the Holy [[Trinity]]. The reasons for other changes were more prosaic, for example where a court of chivalry ordered a change or [[Difference (heraldry)|differencing]] where two families claimed the same arms, as in the famous case of [[Scrope v Grosvenor]]. The resulting two versions of arms are referred to as "France ancient" and "France modern", "Grosvenor ancient" and "Grosvenor modern".
