{{for|other theatres of the same name|Bijou (disambiguation)}} {{Use mdy dates|date=August 2017}} Two [[Broadway theatre]]s have been named the '''Bijou Theatre'''.
==1239 Broadway== [[File:Bijou Theatre, 1239 Broadway, Manhattan.jpg|thumb|upright|1239 Broadway]] The '''Theatre Brighton''',<ref>[[The Sun (New York)|''The Sun'' (New York)]]. August 25, 1878.</ref> at 1239 Broadway between 30th and 31st Streets, had been converted from a drinking and gambling establishment into a theatre for variety, and opened August 26, 1878 with [[Jerry Thomas (bartender)|Jerry Thomas]] as proprietor.<ref>Brown:273</ref> The house had many changes and names until [[McCaull Comic Opera Company|John A. McCaull]], a Baltimore lawyer, and Charles E. Ford took charge of it. Considerable money was spent and when they reöpened the house on March 31, 1880, as the '''Bijou Opera-house''', it looked like a modern and well-regulated theatre.<ref>Brown:274</ref><ref>''The New York Times.'' April 1, 1880</ref> In 1881 and 1882, [[Lillian Russell]] appeared in three different operettas.<ref>''The Sun'' (New York). October 30, 1881</ref><ref>''The New York Times.'' 1881-10-30, 1881-12-20, and June 6, 1882</ref>
But the house proved too small to be profitable,<ref group=note>The plot is only 40 feet wide. See ''The New York Times.'' January 10, 1915.</ref> so after the performance of July 7, 1883 preparations for tearing it down were at once commenced:<ref>''The New York Times.'' July 29, 1883</ref> R. E. J. Miles and Gen. W. B. Barton leased the premises for five years from its owner, Edward F. James. They agreed to advance sufficient funds to erect a new house, which was designed by J. B. McElfatrick & Son and opened December 1, 1883 as the '''Bijou Theatre'''.<ref>''Real Estate Record.'' July 21, 1883</ref> The first production was ''Orpheus and Eurydice,'' an adaption by [[Vera Freeman|Max Freeman]] of [[Jacques Offenbach]]'s ''[[Orpheus in the Underworld|Orfée aux enfers]].''"<ref>Brown:281</ref><ref>''The New York Times.'' August 19, 1883</ref><ref>''The Sun'' (New York). December 2, 1883</ref>
''[[Adonis (musical)|Adonis]]'', starring [[Henry E. Dixey]], played its record-breaking run of 603 performances at the Bijou beginning September 4, 1884. Another long run was ''[[The Music Master]]'', starring [[David Warfield]], transferred from the [[New Victory Theatre|Belasco Theatre]] on January 9, 1905,<ref>''The New York Times.'' January 10, 1905</ref> and playing 511 performances, for a total at the two theaters of 635, before closing September 29, 1906. The next big hit was ''A Gentleman from Mississippi'', starring [[Thomas A. Wise]] and [[Douglas Fairbanks]], which opened September 29, 1908.<ref>''The New York Times.'' September 30, 1908</ref> From June 29 to August 7, 1909, it played at the Aerial Gardens atop the [[New Amsterdam Theatre]], with new scenery and costumes,<ref>''The Sun'' (New York). June 30, 1909</ref> moving back to the Bijou August 9. After giving its 400th performance (counting the Aerial Gardens) on August 25, the play closed on September 18.<ref>''The Sun'' (New York). August 22, 1909.</ref><ref>''The Sun'' (New York). September 10, 1909.</ref>
The Bijou was later used as a silent movie house. It was demolished in 1915 and replaced by the present high-rise office building, which opened in 1917.<ref>Kenrick</ref><ref>''Internet Broadway Database'' website. "Bijou Theatre"</ref><ref>''Emporis'' website</ref>
===Selected shows=== * ''[[Adonis (musical)|Adonis]]'' (1884–86; 603 perf.) * ''[[A Midnight Bell]]'' (1889; 136 perf.) * ''[[The Widow Jones]]'' (1895), basis for 1896 Edison short film ''[[The Kiss (1896 film)|The Kiss]]'' * ''Courted Into Court'' (1896–97; 140 perf.) * ''Sister Mary'' by [[Glen MacDonough]] (1889-1900; 120 perf.) * ''The Climbers'' by [[Clyde Fitch]] (1901; 163 perf.) * ''The Auctioneer'' by [[Charles Klein]] (1901; 105 perf.) * ''Nancy Brown'' (1903; 112 perf.) * ''[[A Gentleman from Mississippi]]'' (1908–09) * ''[[The Music Master]]'' (1905–06; 627 counting 124 shows at Belasco) * ''[[The Lottery Man]]'' (1909–10; 200 perf.)
{{Clear|right}}
==209 West 45th Street== [[File:Bijou Theatre, W. 45th St., Manhattan.jpg|thumb|209 W. 45th St.]] The second '''Bijou Theatre''' was built by the [[Shubert family]] in 1917 at 209 W. 45th Street in [[New York City]].<ref>''Internet Broadway Database'' website. "Toho Cinema"</ref><ref>''Cinema Treasures'' website. "Bijou Theatre"</ref><ref>''The New York Times.'' April 13, 1917</ref> It was one of three theaters that hosted the premiere season of the musical ''[[Fancy Free (musical)|Fancy Free]]''—but primarily it presented plays by many writers, including [[Sacha Guitry]], [[John Galsworthy]], [[A. A. Milne]], [[J. M. Barrie|James M. Barrie]], [[Herman J. Mankiewicz]], [[Leslie Howard (actor)|Leslie Howard]], [[Anton Chekhov]], [[Henrik Ibsen]], [[Luigi Pirandello]], [[Graham Greene]], [[Eugene O'Neill]], [[William Saroyan]], and [[Seán O'Casey]].
In 1950, as the Bijou, it hosted one film, ''[[Cyrano de Bergerac (1950 film)|Cyrano de Bergerac]]'', starring [[José Ferrer]].<ref>''The New York Times.'' November 17, 1950</ref>
In 1951, it became a [[CBS]] radio studio, then{{mdash}}as the '''[[D. W. Griffith]] Theatre'''{{mdash}}it presented [[art film]]s. It was reinstated as the Bijou Theatre in 1965, but was demolished in 1982 to make room for the [[New York Marriott Marquis|Marriott Marquis Hotel]]. {{Clear|right}}
