[[File:Goncourt.jpg|thumb|<center>Edmond and Jules de Goncourt</center>]]

'''The Goncourt Journal''' was a diary written in collaboration by the brothers [[Edmond de Goncourt|Edmond]] and [[Jules de Goncourt]] from 1850 up to Jules' death in 1870, and then by Edmond alone up to a few weeks before his own death in 1896.  It forms an unrivalled and entirely candid chronicle of the literary and artistic Parisian world in which they lived, "a world", it has been said, "of bitter rivalries and bitterer friendships, in which every gathering around a café table on the [[Boulevards of Paris#The grands boulevards|Grands Boulevards]] [was] a chance to raise one's status in the byzantine literary hierarchy".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theparisreview.org/blog/2015/07/21/whats-the-use |title=What's the Use? |last=Burton |first=Tara Isabella |date=21 July 2015 |website=The Paris Review |access-date=13 January 2018 }}</ref>  Fear of lawsuits by the Goncourts' friends and their heirs prevented publication of anything but carefully chosen selections from the Journal for many years, but a complete edition of the original French text appeared in the 1950s in 22 volumes, and there have been several selective translations into English.

==The process of collaboration==

The [[Goncourt brothers]] formed a very close literary partnership. Not only were all of their novels, dramas and non-fiction works written in collaboration until Jules' death but, more surprisingly, so was their Journal.{{sfn|Lyons|2012}}  The Journal was produced by a process [[Edmond de Goncourt|Edmond]] called "dual dictation", one brother dictating to the other and each revising the other's work. Their styles were so similar that it is impossible to tell which brother was writing any particular passage.{{sfn|Robb|2007|ref=harv}}{{sfn|Baldick|1984|p=ix}} For the most part they wrote the Journal late at night, without much consideration about literary style, and there are therefore few of the laboured mannerisms that characterize their novels. Edmond himself admitted that because the journal entries were "hastily set down on paper and not always re-read, our syntax is sometimes happy-go-lucky and not all our words have passports",{{sfn|Baldick|1984|pp=xiv, xix-xx}} and they particularly delighted in accurately recording the slanginess and vulgarity of ordinary speech.{{sfn|Becker|Philips|1971|p=10}}  The collaboration came to an end with Jules' decline and early death from syphilis, recorded by his brother in excruciating detail. When that story drew to its close Edmond initially decided to abandon the Journal, but he took it up again in time to give a detailed description of life during the [[Franco-Prussian War]], the [[Siege of Paris (1870–71)|siege of Paris]], and the [[Paris Commune|Commune]].{{sfn|Dyer|2006}} Some critics find that the Journal improved when Edmond resumed it without Jules.{{sfn|Anonymous|1962}}{{sfn|Anonymous|n.d.}}

==The Journal's accuracy==

The many accounts of conversations in the Journal were aided by Edmond's excellent memory, and, according to [[Gustave Flaubert|Flaubert]], by Jules' habit of jotting notes on his shirt-cuff on the spot.{{sfn|Baldick|1984|p=viii}}  [[Ludovic Halévy]], who was present at many of these conversations, gave the brothers credit for extreme accuracy, and similarly the narrator of [[Marcel Proust|Proust]]'s ''[[In Search of Lost Time#Volume Seven: Time Regained|Le Temps retrouvé]]'' thought that Edmond de Goncourt "knew how to listen, just as he knew how to see"; but some among the Goncourts' contemporaries claimed that the brothers either consciously or unconsciously distorted the conversations they recorded.  The painter Jacques Blanche, for example, said that "nothing is less true than their journals", though [[André Gide]], who thoroughly enjoyed the Journal's accounts of conversations, retorted that that would make the Goncourts' achievement as original artists all the greater.{{sfn|Dyer|2006}}{{sfn|Baldick|1984|p=xiv}}

==Treatment of their friends==

The Goncourt's Journal was started on the same day that they published their first novel, 2 December 1851, which was unluckily also the day that [[Napoleon III|Louis-Napoleon]] launched his ''coup d' état'', leading to the imposition of martial law in Paris.  In this turmoil the novel passed almost unnoticed.  The Goncourts' disappointment over this failure was duly recorded in the Journal, thereby setting the dominant tone for the remaining 45 years.  Poor sales, poor reviews, and the undeserved successes of their literary friends are recorded in meticulous detail.  "Oh, if one of [[Fyodor Dostoyevsky|Dostoyevsky]]'s novels, whose black melancholy is regarded with such indulgent admiration, were signed with the name of Goncourt, what a slating it would get all along the line."{{sfn|Dyer|2006}}  [[Émile Zola|Zola]] was one friend who came in for especially barbed comment, since the Goncourts felt that his subject matter and literary techniques had been borrowed from theirs. "The critics may say what they like about Zola, they cannot prevent us, my brother and myself, from being the John-the-Baptists of modern neurosis."{{sfn|Baldick|1984|p=238}}{{sfn|Dyer|2006}}  Some few friends did come in for sympathetic treatment, notably Princess [[Mathilde Bonaparte]], [[Paul Gavarni]], [[Théophile Gautier]], [[Alphonse Daudet]] and, initially at least, Gustave Flaubert and [[Paul Bins, comte de Saint-Victor|Paul de Saint-Victor]].{{sfn|James|1984|pp=413-414}}{{sfn|Becker|Philips|1971|pp=5-6}}  The critic [[Charles Augustin Sainte-Beuve]] regularly appeared in the Journal, as did the painter [[Edgar Degas]] and the sculptor [[Auguste Rodin]].{{sfn|Baldick|1984|p=xiv}}<ref>{{cite book |last1=Grout |first1=Caroline Franklin |year=1999 |title=Heures d'autrefois (Mémoirs inédits), Souvenirs intimes et autres textes |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=r7q4BgAAQBAJ&pg=PA241&dq=%22Zola+et+Daudet+Flaubert%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjGp9yS49XYAhUCUlAKHeRpCuMQ6AEIKTAA#v=onepage&q=%22Zola%20et%20Daudet%20Flaubert%22&f=false |language=French |location=[Mont-Saint-Aignan] |publisher=Publications de l'Université de Rouen |page=241 |isbn=9782877752701 |access-date=13 January 2018 }}</ref>  Appearances are also made by [[Heinrich Heine]], [[Charles Baudelaire]], [[Victor Hugo]], [[Ernest Renan]], [[Hippolyte Taine]], [[Joris-Karl Huysmans]], [[Guy de Maupassant]], [[Alexandre Dumas|Alexandre Dumas ''père'']] and ''[[Alexandre Dumas, fils|fils]]'', [[Stéphane Mallarmé]], [[Georg Brandes]], [[Ivan Turgenev]] and [[Oscar Wilde]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.perlentaucher.de/buch/edmond-de-goncourt-jules-de-goncourt/journal-1851-1896.html |title=Edmond de Goncourt, Jules de Goncourt. Journal 1851-1896 |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=n.d. |website=Perlentaucher. Das Kulturmagazin |language=German |access-date=14 January 2018 }}</ref>{{sfn|Becker|Philips|1971|p=8}}  Not surprisingly, the often backbiting tone of the Journal led to strained relations with Edmond's surviving friends when they came to read his treatment of them in the published volumes.  As late as the 1950s the Daudet family, concerned for the reputation of their ancestor Alphonse, were still trying to block publication of the complete Journal.{{sfn|Baldick|1984|pp=ix-xiii}}

==Publication==

A few carefully chosen selections from the Journal were published by the Goncourts in a now little-known book, ''Idées et Sensations'' (1866; new edition 1877).<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Bersani |first1=Jacques |date=2008 |title=''Idées et Sensations'' ou les Goncourt en court |url=http://www.persee.fr/doc/cejdg_1243-8170_2008_num_1_15_999 |journal=Cahiers Edmond et Jules de Goncourt |volume=15 |page=53 |language=French |access-date=14 January 2018 }}</ref>  In 1886 Edmond published in ''Le Figaro'' some extracts from the Journal dating from the years before Jules' death, and the following year a more substantial selection of letters from the same years appeared in book form under the title ''Journal des Goncourt: Mémoires de la vie littéraire''.  Eight more volumes were published at the rate of roughly one a year, some being first serialized in ''[[L'Écho de Paris]]''.  The last volume appeared in May 1896, two months before Edmond's death.{{sfn|Baldick|1984|pp=ix-xii}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://copac.jisc.ac.uk/id/28362297?style=html&title=Journal%20des%20Goncourt.%20Me%CC%81moires%20de%20la%20vie%20litte%CC%81raire. |title=Catalogue entry |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=n.d. |website=Copac |access-date=15 January 2018 }}</ref>

==Reception==

''[[Le Figaro]]'' called the first volume a masterpiece of conceit.  Worse, after three weeks only 2000 copies had been sold, provoking Edmond to say "Really, for a result like that it is not worth risking duels".{{sfn|Baldick|1984|p=ix}}  ''Le Figaro'' continued its attacks, writing on the publication of Edmond's fourth volume "He listens and thinks he can hear, he looks and thinks he can see…Of the literary élite of his age…the best of their kind, all that he has managed to give us most of the time is a grotesque and often repulsive picture".  The seventh volume called forth hostile articles in the ''[[Journal des débats]]'' and the ''[[Le Courrier français (1884–1914)|Courrier français]]'', while ''Le Figaro'' reported that a Funeral Committee was being set up on Edmond's behalf.  Excrement was sent to him through the post.{{sfn|Baldick|1984|p=xi}}  

On the other hand [[Anatole France]] wrote that "this perfectly private 
journal is at the same time perfectly literary", and absolved the Goncourts of indiscretion because "[t]hey neither heard nor saw except in art and for 
art".<ref>{{cite book |last1=France |first1=Anatole |translator-last=Evans |translator-first=A. W. |year=1922 |title=On Life & Letters. First Series |url=https://archive.org/stream/onlifeandletters00franiala#page/78/mode/1up |location=New York |publisher=John Lane |page=78 |access-date=15 January 2018 }}</ref>  To American critics the Goncourts' indiscretion naturally seemed less immediately alarming than to most of their French colleagues.  The ''[[The Atlantic|Atlantic Monthly]]'' thought that in fifty years time it would be "the most fascinating and vivid history in existence of the literary and artistic life of Paris during the last half of [the 19th] century", but that its portrait of the close partnership of the Goncourts themselves was of still greater interest.<ref>{{cite journal |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=1893 |title=Contributors' Club |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=q4kRAAAAMAAJ |journal=The Atlantic Monthly |volume=72 |page=857 |access-date=14 January 2018 }}</ref>  [[Henry James]], writing in ''[[The Fortnightly Review]]'', thought that both the Journal and its authors would have been improved if they had not restricted their social life to a narrow coterie: "The Journal…is mainly a record of resentment and suffering, and to this circumstance they attribute many causes; but we suspect that the real cause is for them too the inconvenience from which we suffer as readers – simply the want of space and air."{{sfn|James|1984|p=413}}  

After Edmond's death Proust paid the Journal the tribute of including a pastiche of it in his ''[[In Search of Lost Time|À la recherche du temps perdu]]'', and indeed the Journal's obsessive collecting of the most minute details of its authors' social life and rendering of them into literary art has been said to anticipate the supposed innovations of Proust.{{sfn|Noiray|2005|p=198}}<ref> {{cite book |last1=Bouillaguet |first1=Annick |year=1996 |title=Proust et les Goncourts: le pastiche du ''Journal'' dans ''Le temps retrouvé'' |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=yQsQAQAAIAAJ |language=French |location=Paris |publisher=Lettres modernes |pages=passim |nopp=y |isbn=9782256904608 |access-date=14 January 2018 }}</ref>  In 1940 [[Christopher Isherwood]] confided in his own journal that "Here, gossip achieves the epigrammatic significance of poetry".<ref>{{cite book |last1=Isherwood |first1=Christopher |year=2011 |title=Diaries. Volume 1: 1939-1960 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=8kDu-EzTf-4C |location=London |publisher=Vintage |page=96 |isbn=9780099555827 |access-date=14 January 2018 }}</ref>  As late as 1962 one reviewer found it necessary to warn his more delicate readers about the scabrousness of much of the conversation recorded,{{sfn|Anonymous|1962}} and in 1971 the Goncourts' translators George J. Becker and Edith Philips wrote of the emotional detachment, even heartlessness, to be found everywhere in the journal except in those passages that depict Edmond's relationship with his brother and with Daudet.{{sfn|Becker|Philips|1971|pp=10-11}}  In more recent years Jacques Noiray called it "a modern ''[[La Comédie humaine|Comédie humaine]]'' of the republic of letters",{{sfn|Noiray|2005|p=197}} while according to another literary scholar, David Baguley, the Journal is "an immense machine for transforming lived experience into documentary form", to be used as raw material by the Goncourts when writing their novels.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Baguley |first1=David |year=1997 |chapter=Le ''Journal'' des Goncourt, document naturaliste |editor1-last=Cabanès |editor1-first=Jean-Louis |title=Les frères Goncourt: art et écriture |language=French |location=Talence |publisher=Presses universitaires de Bordeaux |page=107 ''et seq.'' |isbn=2867812011 }}</ref>  

In the 21st century the Journal's repute is as high as ever.  The German satirist [[Harald Schmidt]] has called it "the greatest gossip in world literature – it's sensational!",<ref>{{cite news |last=Schmidt |first=Jochen |date=28 November 2014 |title="Endlich mal Geistesverwandte entdeckt" |url=https://www.tagesanzeiger.ch/leben/gesellschaft/Endlich-mal-Geistesverwandte-entdeckt/story/10871152  |work=Tages-Anzeiger |language=German |location=Zurich |access-date=14 January 2018 }}</ref> and for the historian [[Graham Robb]] it is "one of the longest, most absorbing, and most enlightening diaries in European literature".{{sfn|Robb|2007|ref=harv}}  The critic [[Adam Kirsch]] attributes the modern age's interest in late-19th century French literary life to the Goncourt Journal.{{sfn|Kirsch|2006}}

==Modern editions==

By Edmond's will, the manuscripts of the Journal were bequeathed to the [[Académie Goncourt]], itself a creation of the same will, with instructions that they be strictly protected from public scrutiny for 20 years in the vaults of the ''[[Bibliothèque nationale de France]]'', after which they were to be made public either by allowing access to them or by publication in print.  In the event, the Académie did neither of these things in 1916, fearing libel actions,<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=The Goncourt Journal |url=http://find.galegroup.com/ttda/infomark.do?&source=gale&prodId=TTDA&userGroupName=bright&tabID=T003&docPage=article&searchType=BasicSearchForm&docId=CS118690066&type=multipage&contentSet=LTO&version=1.0
|work=The Times |location=London |date=18 August 1921 |access-date=14 January 2018 }}</ref>{{sfn|Baldick|1984|pp=xii-xiii}} though the public were finally allowed to see the manuscripts in 1925.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=The de Goncourt MSS |url=http://find.galegroup.com/ttda/infomark.do?&source=gale&prodId=TTDA&userGroupName=bright&tabID=T003&docPage=article&searchType=BasicSearchForm&docId=CS151853334&type=multipage&contentSet=LTO&version=1.0 |work=The Times |location=London |date=22 August 1925 |access-date=14 January 2018 }}</ref>  In 1935-1936 the Académie did produce an "''édition définitive''", albeit a selective one, in nine volumes,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://academie-goncourt.fr/?article=1229173796 |title=Le journal des Goncourt |last=Dabadie |first=Marie |date=n.d. |website=Académie Goncourt |language=French |access-date=14 January 2018 }}</ref>{{sfn|Anonymous|n.d.}}{{sfn|Noiray|2005|p=197}} and in 1945 they announced that a complete edition would appear the following year.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Delayed Action |url=http://find.galegroup.com/ttda/infomark.do?&source=gale&prodId=TTDA&userGroupName=bright&tabID=T003&docPage=article&searchType=BasicSearchForm&docId=CS84623689&type=multipage&contentSet=LTO&version=1.0 |work=The Times |location=London |date=9 October 1945 |access-date=14 January 2018 }}</ref>  This proved to be far too optimistic, the first editor, Robert Burnand, still having not brought the project to completion at his death in 1953.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Brunel |first1=C.  |date=1953 |title=Robert Burnand |url=http://www.persee.fr/doc/bec_0373-6237_1953_num_111_1_460264 |journal=Bibliothèque de l'École des chartes |volume=111 |page=344 |language=French |access-date=14 January 2018 }}</ref>  The editorship was taken over by Robert Ricatte, and it was finally published in 22 volumes between 1956 and 1959.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Grant |first1=Richard B. |year=1972 |title=The Goncourt Brothers |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=m7FcAAAAMAAJ&q=%221956-59,+in+22+volumes.+Recently%22&dq=%221956-59,+in+22+volumes.+Recently%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwix8t_s_9fYAhWBY1AKHdhlCOgQ6AEIKTAA |location=New York |publisher=Twayne |page=159 |access-date=14 January 2018 }}</ref>  A new multi-volume edition, the work of a large editorial team under the direction of Jean-Louis Cabanès, began to appear in 2005.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://goncourt-dramaturges.e-monsite.com/pages/bibliographie-1.html#B4 |title=Bibliographie |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=n.d. |website=Les Goncourt dramaturges |publisher=E-Monsite |language=French |access-date=14 January 2018 }}</ref>{{sfn|Noiray|2005|p=197}}

==Translations==

No complete translation of the Goncourt Journal into English has ever appeared, but there have been several selections.  The first, ''Edmond and Jules de Goncourt: With Letters and Leaves from their Journals'', compiled and translated by [[Marie Belloc Lowndes|Marie Belloc]] and [[Marie L. Shedlock]], appeared in two volumes as early as 1895, before the nine volumes of Edmond de Goncourt's edition had yet been completed.{{sfn|Lyons|2012}}  This was followed by [[Julius West]]'s ''The Journal of the Goncourts'' in 1908, and by Lewis Galantière's ''The Goncourt Journals 1851-1870'' in 1937.{{sfn|Anonymous|n.d.}}  In 1962 [[Oxford University Press]] published Robert Baldick's much-praised ''Pages from the Goncourt Journal'', reprinted in 1984 by [[Penguin Books]] and in 2006 by [[New York Review Books]].{{sfn|Baldick|1984|p=[iv]}}{{sfn|Kirsch|2006}}  George J. Becker has also edited and translated two thematic selections: ''Paris Under Siege, 1870-1871'' (1969), and (in collaboration with Edith Philips) ''Paris and the Arts, 1851-1896'' (1971).{{sfn|Anonymous|n.d.}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://copac.jisc.ac.uk/id/34664585?style=html&title=Paris%20and%20the%20arts%2C%201851-1896from%20the%20%22Goncourt%20Journal%22 |title=Catalogue entry |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=n.d. |website=Copac |access-date=14 January 2018 }}</ref>

