{{Infobox book | name = The Emergence of Probability: A Philosophical Study of Early Ideas about Probability, Induction and Statistical Inference | image = File:The Emergence of Probability, first edition.jpg | caption = Cover of the first edition | author = [[Ian Hacking]] | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = | language = English | series = | subject = History of probability | published = 1975 | media_type = Print ([[Hardcover]] and [[Paperback]]) | pages = | isbn = 978-0521685573 | dewey= | congress= | oclc= | preceded_by = | followed_by = }} '''''The Emergence of Probability: A Philosophical Study of Early Ideas about Probability, Induction and Statistical Inference''''' is a 1975 book by the philosopher [[Ian Hacking]].
==Reception== Hacking's work has been described as ground-breaking.<ref>[[#Mac05|Macintosh 2005]]. p. 357.</ref>
The philosopher [[James Franklin (philosopher)|James Franklin]] argued that Hacking's contention that there was no concept of uncertain evidence before about 1650 is incorrect, as it neglects the extensive Latin [[scholasticism|scholastic]] literature on legal [[evidence (law)|evidence]] and [[aleatory contracts]] and on [[inductive reasoning|induction]].<ref name="Franklin">[[#Fra01|Franklin 2001]]. p. 373.</ref>
